name: trans-1,4-cyclohexanedicarboxylic acid
source: Journal of the Indian Institute of Science
Reason: The basic unit for this compound could be considered as cyclohexane, which has a melting point of approximately 6.5°C. Two carboxylic acid groups attached to the cyclohexane ring will significantly increase the melting point. Carboxylic acids have a strong capability to form hydrogen bonds which leads to a higher melting point. Also, the trans-configuration of the dicarboxylic acid groups on the cyclohexane ring may result in a more stable and tightly packed crystal lattice as compared to the cis-configuration. Since each carboxylic acid group can potentially raise the melting point by a significant amount (an estimated 100-150°C per carboxylic group due to the extensive hydrogen bonding possible between molecules), we can predict an additive effect. There may be additional stabilization due to the rigidity of the trans-cyclohexane ring which can further increase melting point.
